	  <title>Quiz on Invertible Linear Transformations</title>
	
	
	  <quiz>
		    <question>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Is the counterclockwise rotation of the plane about the origin through the angle <math>
                  <latex>\theta</latex>
               </math> invertible?</para.body>
         </para>
			      <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
            <img src="ims/Rotation.png"/>
         </media>
		    </question>
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>R_{\theta}</latex>
                  </math> is invertible</para.body>
            </para>
         </answer>
			      <info>
            <para>
               <para.body>Correct! – The inverse of <math>
                     <latex>R_{\theta}</latex>
                  </math> is <math>
                     <latex>R_{-\theta}</latex>
                  </math>; i.e. the rotation of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                  </math> about the origin through the angle <math>
                     <latex>\theta</latex>
                  </math> in the clockwise direction.</para.body>
            </para>
         </info>
		    </choice>
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
            <para>
               <para.body>
                  <math>
                     <latex>R_{\theta}</latex>
                  </math> is not invertible.</para.body>
            </para>
         </answer>
			      <info>
            <para>
               <para.body>Sorry! – No. The question here is if the transformation effect of <math>
                     <latex>R_{\theta}</latex>
                  </math> can be reversed. Why do you think this would not be the case?</para.body>
            </para>
         </info>
		    </choice>
	  </quiz>
	
	  <quiz>
		    <question>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Is the reflection of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math> about a hyperspace invertible?</para.body>
         </para>
			      <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
            <img src="ims/LeftHandMirrorRightHand.jpg"/>
         </media>
		    </question>
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
            <para>
               <para.body>Yes! Such a reflection is invertible</para.body>
            </para>
         </answer>
			      <info>
            <para>
               <para.body>Correct!</para.body>
            </para>
         </info>
		    </choice>
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
            <para>
               <para.body>No! Such a reflection is not invertible</para.body>
            </para>
         </answer>
			      <info>
            <para>
               <para.body>Sorry! No!</para.body>
            </para>
         </info>
		    </choice>
	  </quiz>
	
	  <quiz>
		    <question>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Is the projection of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math> onto the <math>
                  <latex>xy</latex>
               </math>-plane invertible?</para.body>
         </para>
		    </question>
		    <hint>
			      <info>
				        <para>
               <para.body>Visualize the effect of this projection on an object: Shine a light vertically onto the object. Its shadow in the <math>
                     <latex>xy</latex>
                  </math>-plane is the outcome of the projection. Therefore the question is: can you always recover the original object from its shadow.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </info>
		    </hint>
		
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
            <para>
               <para.body>Yes! This projection is invertible.</para.body>
            </para>
         </answer>
			      <info>
            <para>
               <para.body>Sorry! No. – To see why such a projection is not invertible, consider the case where the projection of an object is a single point. In this case we do not know if the original is a single point or a vertical stick. Nor do we know how far either of these objects is from the <math>
                     <latex>xy</latex>
                  </math>-plane. Therefore such a projection is not invertible.</para.body>
            </para>
         </info>
		    </choice>
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
            <para>
               <para.body>No! This projection is not invertible.</para.body>
            </para>
         </answer>
			      <info>
            <para>
               <para.body>Correct! – Why is it not invertible?</para.body>
            </para>
         </info>
		    </choice>
	  </quiz>
	
	
	  <quiz>
		    <question>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Is a shear transformation of <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math> parallel to the <math>
                  <latex>x</latex>
               </math>-axis invertible?</para.body>
         </para>
			      <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
            <img src="ims/ShearR2_3.png"/>
         </media>
		    </question>
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
				        <para>
               <para.body>Yes! Such a  shear transformation is invertible.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </answer>
			      <info>
				        <para>
               <para.body>Correct! – – Why is a shear transformation invertible? If the original shear transformation has shear vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{s}</latex>
                  </math>, then the shear transformation with shear vector <math>
                     <latex>-\Vect{s}</latex>
                  </math> will restore each point and each object in its original position.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </info>
		    </choice>
		    <choice>
			      <answer>
				        <para>
               <para.body>No! Such a transformation is not invertible.</para.body>
            </para>
			      </answer>
			      <info>
            <para>
               <para.body>Sorry! No!</para.body>
            </para>
         </info>
		    </choice>
		
	  </quiz>
	
</quiz.pack>
